# Security Rules

> Stack-agnostic baseline. A stack with its own security profile (web app, data pipeline,
> service) adds rules on top — record those in `CLAUDE.md`. Nothing here is optional.

## Secrets Management
- NEVER hardcode API keys, tokens, passwords, connection strings, or credentials in source.
- Read secrets from environment variables or a secrets manager — never from committed files.
- `.env` and any local secrets file must be gitignored; this project keeps them in
  `.claude/.local/` (gitignored).
- No secrets in comments, logs, error messages, test fixtures, or sample data.

## Input Handling
- Treat all external input as untrusted: validate at the boundary, then trust internally.
- Validate on the authoritative side (the server / the trusted process) — client-side
  checks are UX, not security.
- Allow-list expected shapes/values rather than block-listing bad ones where possible.

## Injection
- Use parameterized queries / prepared statements for any data store — never build a query
  by string concatenation of untrusted input.
- Escape or contextually encode untrusted data at the point it is rendered or interpolated
  (HTML, shell, query, template).
- Never pass untrusted input to a shell or `eval`-like construct.

## Output & Error Hygiene
- Do not leak internal errors, stack traces, secrets, or internal paths to users or logs
  that cross a trust boundary.
- Fail closed: on an auth/validation error, deny — do not fall through to a permissive path.

## Dependencies & Supply Chain
- Pin dependency versions; track and remediate known advisories (see `dependency-governance.md`).
- Load remote/third-party resources only from trusted sources, pinned to a specific version,
  with integrity verification where the platform supports it.

## Access & Least Privilege
- Grant the minimum privilege required; scope tokens and roles narrowly.
- Read-only by default for analysis/inspection paths; mutation requires explicit intent and approval.
